      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T10:24:00Z",
      "webTitle":"Credit crunch figurehead Adam Applegarth 'quits private equity firm'",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/17/adam-applegarth-quits-private-equity-apollo",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/oct/17/adam-applegarth-quits-private-equity-apollo",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Ex-Northern Rock boss, who presided over first bank run since 1866, resigns as Apollo adviser, according to reports",
        "headline":"Credit crunch figurehead Adam Applegarth 'quits private equity firm'",
        "body":"<p>The former boss of Northern Rock, Adam Applegarth, has left the private equity firm he joined four years ago with the hope of rehabilitating himself following the banking crisis.</p><p>Applegarth had <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2009/oct/01/disgraced-northern-rock-boss-job\" title=\"\">joined Apollo Global Management in the autumn of 2009</a>, two years after the run on the Newcastle-based lender that eventually led to the bank's nationalisation. He had presided over the first run on a bank since 1866 and later described 9 August 2007 as the \"day the world changed\", marking the start of the credit crunch which froze the bank out of the wholesale markets on which it relied for financing.</p><p><a href=\"http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/business/industries/banking/article3896776.ece\" title=\"\">According to the Times</a>, he has now resigned as an adviser to Apollo after causing controversy by becoming involved in bids for parts of Northern Rock and the 314 branches which Royal Bank of Scotland needed to sell. They are now being sold to a consortium involving the Church of England.</p><p>Officials from Apollo were not available for comment but the resignation of Applegarth comes as the roles of former bankers during the crisis have been subjected to fresh scrutiny following the report into the collapse of HBOS. James Crosby, the former boss of HBOS, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/jun/11/hbos-james-crosby-formally-stripped-knighthood\" title=\"\">gave back his knighthood after criticism by the parliamentary commission on banking standards</a>.</p><p>Applegarth quit Northern Rock in December 2007 – two months before Alistair Darling stepped in to nationalise the former building society – with a payoff of around £760,000, ending a 20-year career with the bank which he had joined as graduate trainee.</p><p>The government later split Northern Rock into two: a \"good\" bank which has been bought by Sir Richard Branson's Virgin Money and a \"bad\" bank which is still owned by taxpayers and part of UK Asset Resolution, which is running down the remaining loans.</p><p>It is not clear how much Applegarth has been paid over the past four years by Apollo, which specialises in buying distressed loans and securities.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420241190|2013-10-17T12:53:02Z|1dddf7216a40e3bab2fe4141394ea4a859148d04 -->",
