      "id":"business/2013/oct/17/online-sales-surge-uk-retailers",
      "sectionId":"business",
      "sectionName":"Business",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T09:54:54Z",
      "webTitle":"Surge in online sales plus demand for new furniture boost UK retailers",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/17/online-sales-surge-uk-retailers",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/business/2013/oct/17/online-sales-surge-uk-retailers",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Retail recovery in September pushes sales to biggest quarter-on-quarter rise since March 2008",
        "headline":"Surge in online sales plus demand for new furniture boost UK retailers",
        "body":"<p>Britain's retailers returned to health last month on the back of strong demand for new furniture and a 20% year-on-year surge in online sales, according to official figures.</p><p>After a 2.1% fall in August, the Office for National Statistics said retail sales rose by 0.7% month on month in September, excluding petrol sales, following a 3% surge in the purchase of household goods.</p><p>The rise in furniture sales and other household goods was credited by many analysts to the buoyant mood in the housing market. After a short time-lag, the government's Help to Buy deposit insurance scheme and the Bank of England's funding for lending initiative, which has depressed mortgage rates, appear to have pushed up the number of transactions and the demand for homeware.</p><p>The ONS said a look back over the previous three months revealed a period of growth, with retail sales up 1.5% quarter on quarter.</p><p>\"This is the largest quarter-on-quarter rise since March 2008 when the economy as a whole was at its peak, before the economic downturn,\" it said.</p><p>Alan Clarke, UK economist at Scotia Bank, described the figures as solid and unspectacular.</p><p>Chris Williamson, chief economist at financial data provider Markit, said: \"Retail sales showed a welcome revival in September after dipping in August, adding further to mounting evidence that the economy grew strongly in the third quarter. The three months to September have been the best quarter the retail sector has seen the start of 2008, suggesting an encouraging lead-up to the all-important Christmas season.\"</p><p>He said: \"The upturn corroborates data from Visa, which showed a wider measure of total consumer spending up a buoyant 1.5% during September.\"</p><p>Consumer confidence, which has risen sharply in recent months largely because people have been busier at work, has driven incomes higher and provided greater job security, he said.</p><p>\"<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/economics-blog/2013/oct/16/employment-growing-wage-slaves-ons-prices-pay\" title=\"\">Employment jumped higher in August</a>, pushing the number of jobless benefits claimants down at the fastest rate since 1997. Rising house prices have added to the feel-good factor,\" he added.</p><p>Clarke said that based on surveys of manufacturing, construction and services industries, GDP should rise by 1.2% quarter on quarter.</p><p>The first estimate of GDP growth in the third quarter is published on 25 October and economists' estimates vary from 0.7% to 1.2%.</p><p>\"It's just that lacklustre industrial production data, the soggy July monthly services reading and mediocre retail sales have undermined faith in a super-strong outcome,\" Clarke said.</p><p>In <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/business/2013/oct/16/bank-of-england-interest-rates-may-rise-next-year\" title=\"\">an interview with the Guardian</a> on Wednesday, Spencer Dale, the Bank of England's chief economist, pointed to a strong GDP number when he said the economy was \"growing at something like 3-4% annualised\".</p><p>Dale said it was possible Threadneedle Street would raise interest rates as early as next year if the strength of the recovery was maintained.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420237666|2013-10-17T12:53:02Z|771d41ac02a2c24146a962b881689e638f179918 -->",
