      "id":"media/2013/oct/17/bskyb-profits-bt-premier-league",
      "sectionId":"media",
      "sectionName":"Media",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-10-17T10:30:00Z",
      "webTitle":"BSkyB profits hit by tussle with BT over Premier League",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/oct/17/bskyb-profits-bt-premier-league",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/media/2013/oct/17/bskyb-profits-bt-premier-league",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"Costs of £2.3bn rights deal hit bottom line in fiscal first quarter, but TV and broadband subscriptions show healthy growth. By <strong>Mark Sweney</strong>",
        "headline":"BSkyB profits hit by tussle with BT over Premier League",
        "body":"<p>BSkyB has reported an 8% fall in profits to £285m in the three months to the end of September, as investment in new services and costs incurred in its Premier League battle with pay-TV rival BT took its toll.</p><p></p><p>BSkyB's adjusted operating profits were hit by the £2.3bn deal it was forced to make to stop BT from securing the lion's share of Premier League matches for the next three years, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/jun/13/premier-league-tv-rights-3-billion-sky-bt\" title=\"\">a 40% increase on the last deal</a>, although the company said the dip was \"in line with expectations\".</p><p></p><p>The satellite broadcaster said that the new deal it has with the Premier League sees the amount it pays each year rise by £220m, from the previous £540m a year to £760m.</p><p></p><p>BSkyB saw churn – the rate of customers leaving its business – rise slightly in the quarter by 0.1% to 11%.</p><p></p><p>The fairly stable churn rate would appear to indicate that the promotional offers available from BT, such as free TV sports packages to customers who take broadband, are not yet damaging Sky.</p><p></p><p>Investors reacted warmly to the results, with BSkyB's share price rising 4%, or 34.5p, to 912.5p in early trading.</p><p></p><p>Sky said that TV viewing of the first 23 live Premier League games was up 20% year on year, which excludes viewing on mobile devices.</p><p></p><p>\"The rise has come from across the board,\" said the BSkyB chief executive, Jeremy Darroch. \"Core viewing to our live channels is [85%] up with the switch from Saturday lunch to Saturday evening matches [under the new TV rights deal] which has been a big part of the schedule.\"</p><p></p><p>BSkyB is expecting another serious challenge from BT when Champions League TV rights come up next year, although Darroch played down the impact of what is expected to be a massive increase in the cost of the previous deal.</p><p></p><p>\"In terms of content inflation [cost increase for rights] I'm very happy,\" he said. \"This quarter programming costs went up less than sales – that has been the trend for a while.\"</p><p></p><p>BSkyB reported 7% growth in revenue in the quarter to £1.84bn as total viewing to its Sky Sports channels rose 15% on last year, fuelled by a summer of sport that included England's triumphant battle for the Ashes against Australia and successful Lions rugby tour.</p><p></p><p>TV subscriber numbers, which include subscribers to its satellite TV channels as well as internet service Now TV, rose by 37,000 in the quarter to 10.45m.</p><p></p><p>Viewing of Sky Sports via mobile TV service Sky Go rose 40% year on year, while watching of movies on the service increased by 50%. Its premium paid-for service Sky Go Extra, which allows customers to register up to four devices and download TV and movies to watch offline for £5 a month, saw users rise 219,000 to a total of 385,000.</p><p></p><p>Sky added 111,000 new broadband subscribers in the quarter, a 9% year-on-year increase, to take its total customer base to more than 5 million.</p><p></p><p>Those taking Sky's high definition service rose 107,000 to 4.89 million.</p><p></p><p>Sky HD service subscriptions grew by 642,000, taking the total number of customers to 3.4 million, with growth running at 50,000 a week.</p><p></p><p>The rapid rise in the penetration of the internet-connected Sky+HD boxes is helping to fuel a surge in on-demand usage.</p><p></p><p>There was a fourfold increase in weekly downloads through Sky's on-demand services, while movie rentals via Sky Store have doubled year on year.</p><p></p><p>Triple-play customers, those taking three products from Sky, rose to 36% of the total customer base.</p><p></p><p>Programming costs were up 6% to £622m, due to a \"step-up\" in Premier League costs and investment in original UK TV commissions.</p><p></p><p>Advertising revenues rose 7% to £102m.</p><p></p><p>Darroch said the healthy rise is due to the fact that the London Olympics, which aired on the ad-free BBC, dented viewing – and therefore advertising – on commercial channels.</p><p></p><p>Average revenue per user, a key metric watched by analysts, rose by £17 year on year, or 3%, to £559.</p><p></p><p>BSkyB announced in July that it would <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/jul/26/bskyb-annual-results-now-tv\" title=\"\">spend £60m to £70m on developing connected TV services</a>, which include internet service Now TV and the development of a budget £9.99 set-top box.</p><p></p><p>Darroch said that the company would not give an update on the sales of the set-top box, which is aimed at Freeview households, or the progress of the internet service.</p><p></p><p>In July BSkyB said that <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/media/2013/jul/26/bskyb-annual-results-now-tv\" title=\"\">more than 50,000 people</a> had taken advantage of its £9.99 sport \"day pass\", the first time in its two-decade history the pay-TV giant has allowed access to prime content such as Premier League football without a TV subscription.</p><p></p><p>Earlier this week BSkyB reached a deal with arch-rival BT to offer its Sky Movies channels on BT TV.</p><p></p><p>However, Darroch said that the two companies were still at loggerheads over offering Sky Sports to BT customers with internet-connected YouView set-top boxes.</p><p></p><p>The deal is seen as critical to BT, as YouView is the advanced set-top box being pushed to customers, and currently only BT customers with its Vision set-top box are able to get Sky Sports.</p><p></p><p><em>• To contact the MediaGuardian news desk email media@theguardian.com or phone 020 3353 3857. For all other inquiries please call the main Guardian switchboard on 020 3353 2000. If you are writing a comment for publication, please mark clearly \"for publication\".</em></p><p><em>• To get the latest media news to your desktop or mobile, follow MediaGuardian on </em><a href=\"http://twitter.com/mediaguardian\" title=\"\"><em>Twitter</em></a><em> and </em><a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/mediaguardian\" title=\"\"><em>Facebook</em></a><em>.</em></p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/420224262|2013-10-17T12:53:02Z|9d060c309a8abeef38f8211e2f78d262c431873f -->",
